  "prompt": "What are the penalties for money laundering under federal law?",
  "response": "Under federal law, money laundering can result in significant criminal penalties, including:\n\n1. Potential prison sentences:\n- Up to 20 years for each money laundering offense\n- Maximum sentence can increase depending on specific circumstances\n\n2. Financial penalties:\n- Substantial monetary fines\n- Often up to $500,000 or twice the value of the property involved in the transaction\n\n3. Additional consequences:\n- Asset forfeiture\n- Potential seizure of property connected to laundering activities\n- Civil penalties\n- Loss of professional licenses\n\n4. Severity factors:\n- Amount of money involved\n- Frequency of transactions\n- Connection to other criminal activities\n\nExact penalties depend on specific circumstances and federal sentencing guidelines. Prosecution is typically handled by the U.S. Department of Justice.\n\nI want to be clear that I'm providing general legal information, not specific legal advice. Anyone facing potential money laundering charges should consult a qualified criminal defense attorney.",
